segments.text: The black colleges in the South, of course, were originally started by northern missionaries who, I suppose, they've gotten all the labels.
They were the nigger lovers.
They were the persons who believed that black people had this equal opportunity to fight after the Civil War.
And they were hoping that the establishment of colleges would help.
liberate blacks from the problems that they had.
And so, of course, the funding for many of them came from northern churches, and even to this day.
And then, of course, the Negro College Fund eventually was formulated much later.
And, of course, the southern churches
because of various ways, have not been real strong supporters, although I'd have to, I really can't speak intelligently on percentages here.

But, of course, there was a tendency that once they did get started, that the white, predominantly white, denominational churches did give help to the black college as much as they would give missionary aid to sending people to Africa.
same kind of mentality.
Minnesota Conference, which I was a part, really tried to raise a lot of money for West College.
That's why I was involved with it to some degree.
And the pastor of the church where I was serving as a campus minister was on the board of trustees.
There were all these kinds of tie-ins with that, but I saw that kind of mentality of giving.
Again, because
there was a feeling on the part of the people in the northern churches that we ought to do something about our country, you know, in the South.
And I think that was a worthy and noble goal.
And even to this day, there's a need for black colleges, I believe, as well as women's colleges, as well as other kinds of ethnic colleges, because
there's certain, according to research, as I understand it, there's certain self-esteem that is built into people when you have role models of people that are like you.
And I think that's worthy in facing the problems of life that you can see people who are like you succeeding and not feeling the failures that are around when you don't have those role models.
Well, considering that support from the North added the
Well, of course, they were ridiculously bad, because here, even though the college was formed after the Civil War, here we were in 1963.
And, of course, the Civil War was over in 1965, 1865.
And so, here the college was almost 100 years old, and it still wasn't accredited.

it was the last black college of our church that was accredited eventually it is now accredited and of course i heard a story recently about i was talking to an accrediting head of the southern association as a matter of fact because i was on one of these committees here in texas and he pointed out how you know people can get accreditation if they have a lot of money in some
from New York came down to Florida and got this thing accredited in a very short time because they were millions, both millions.
Well, the church just didn't put enough money into that college to get it accredited, and so an unaccredited college does not attract a lot of students.
And so that was a very big problem, and fortunately that has now been overcome.
I don't know if I fully answered your question, but it shows that finances of the church were not given to meet some of these ethnic and minority concerns.
Now, the Methodist Church for the last two quadrenniums has put the ethnic church as number one.
So now, there is a real emphasis in giving towards
these concerns more than any other concerns.
So again, Methodist Church is a national and international leader in this very thing and I'm glad to know that I belong to a church that is trying to practice in all its policies a more equalitarian
than any other denomination or church that I know in the world today.
The ethnic church in the United States or in the world, the missions field, is where the most money is going right now?
Oh, the Methodist Church is always all denominations.
They put more money into their local church than they ever give to missions.
And domestic missions are their own missions.
That's a natural phenomenon.
Did you ever get to meet the professor that you exchanged with?
Yes, I met him.
We visited briefly.
What was his reaction to his experience?
A lot of problems existed in the Mankato area because he was a black person, he was perceived as a black person because he isn't learning.
Just to give you an example, a very strange thing happened.
We had a heating system problem in our house and the heating system would go bang because of various times

he couldn't uniformly get around the pipes and he was scared to death a number of times he thought somebody had bombed the building and of course that was partly due to the fact that that was actually happening in Birmingham there was this terrible bombing and we had racists in Mankato I was I wasn't threatened but I was called
even by some of the people in our congregation, in various derogatory terms, because of my interest in helping in this equality work that we were working on.
So did he give any advice to you all upon returning of things that could be done in your cave in a previous situation?
He wasn't one to give advice on that, and I wasn't one to give advice to him either.
We both were humbled by the experience of living in a way in two different cultures, and yet here we were citizens of the same country.
When did, upon returning home, was that when you first started to hear about the March on Washington, or was that when the works were while in Illinois?
Well, of course, it was the same year that I was in that exchange in the spring.
And then, of course, I was active in student work.
So I think the march in Washington was just a culmination of our expression of frustration over the whole situation.
I mean, people generally don't march unless there's a lot of frustration going on in their hearts and minds.
So this is just a culmination of hundreds of years of frustration that we were expressing.
Frustration in our own religion that was not practicing what it preached.
Frustration in the democracy that was not practicing what it preached.
Frustration in the educational system that was saying certain things in the textbooks, but not really living it out.
in educational institutions, and on and on and on.
Just total frustration with the words of democracy and the lack of practice.
So what were your steps to go to UN as a delegate for the Methodist Church for the Minnesota Conference?
Well, these things happened really quickly.
March on Washington was being organized and there was going to be all this happening and some of us were interested in participating in it and so different kinds of things happened.
At Mankato State different groups were

praying about it, working on it, and decided that certain people ought to be sent as delegates, and then I was a part of a regional system of the Methodist Church, and I was one of the associate deans of the summer camp program that met every year, and they also felt we ought to be a part of this, and so there were
different organizations in the church, both in the local, regional, and national level.
And then there were some of us that volunteered to be a part of this representative process.
So that's how it happened.
So in going to the march, you felt like the main purpose was a mass expression of frustration about the institution you were in?

frustration about the political, religious, and educational, and economic institutions of our country, that we're not living up to the ideals that were written down as practices and policies to follow in dealing with people who are of different races and colors and creeds.

What do you feel was the response from, as an attempt to lobby for Kennedy's moderate civil rights package, and to Martin Luther King said he felt like the march was a subpoena on the conscience of the United States.
What was your response after that day?
Well, I think it was the greatest step forward in American democracy.

even greater than the American Revolution or the Civil War in terms of a positive kind of witness that made us world leaders, I believe, and still world leaders in trying to practice some of these things that we have in our Bible and in the US Constitution.
Which speaker affected you the most?
Well, of course, you know, I could say it was Martin Luther King and his great dramatic speech.
I had a dream there at the memorial, but I'm not sure that that was...
I think the greatest speaker was the Spirit of God working in the midst of our humanity.
The voice of God, the voice of human conscience over all of history, human history.
And these were the voices that I heard.
I think the voice of Christ
Of course, Martin Luther King would quote Christ, and so I saw a, and as far as that goes, it was the voices, you know, universally around the world.
One of the speakers at that day was from the Student Nonviolent Coordinating Committee.
called SNCC.
They came out of the Southern Christian Leadership Conference with Martin Luther King started, and he was a rather militant speaker.
Do you remember that?
Like you said, Louis?
Well, I remember hearing of him, knowing of him.
I never knew him personally, and I, um,
disagreed with a number of the people who ideologically nor practically did I agree with.
Some people felt that although Martin Luther King preached nonviolence, that in effect his preaching of nonviolence was actually inciting violence.
How do you feel about that?
Well, the same criticism was made of Jesus and Gandhi and others.
You remember Jesus, Gandhi, and others did not have a political army, you know.
And what are the alternatives if you don't have an army and computers and missiles?
What are your alternatives to power?
About all you have is the people and mass, or a person as an individual.

But do you think that the changes that were accomplished during that period could have been done without the violence and things that did take place, without the change in the South, the antagonistic attitude towards the South?
Well, you have to measure violence.
Look, when we had war with England,
And we separated from them, and that was, we had a lot of people die.
But it was a small number compared to what died in the Civil War, the largest number in the history of the country.
And neither the issues of the Revolutionary War or the Civil War were settled in any form or fashion, really.
Whereas this did help settle some of the issues that they aren't.
fully worked out, but at least we do have some semblance of American democracy being practiced on all levels of our society now in 1985, whereas we didn't have that in 1865 or in 1776.
We had these paper promises.
Now I think we're beyond paper promises and we do some practical realism.
Nothing's accomplished in this world, unfortunately, save through war or political protest or Pearl Harbor type experiences because of the idiotic behavior of people.
Concrete thinking, people have their minds set in concrete.

And no matter, you know, presently I'm engaged in this suicide youth, teenage situation, but it doesn't affect anybody until a Pearl Harbor happens in a family or a community, and then you can start working.
And I can't tell you why.
I mean, I'm working, and it hasn't happened here, but there's a

a small minority of us that work on these problems of society, whether it be war, suicide, civil rights, poverty, feeding the hungry, saving the environment, we've got terrible problems with acid rain in the environment now, and those are just some of my concerns, and we're just a small number.
And we're all human, we get tired, we don't have money, but
Sometimes we have to use large crowds.
Sometimes we have to use the mass media.
Sometimes we have to use protest letters to make it.
Well, I guess what I'm referring to is something like the Selma March, where the marchers tried to cross that bridge for days.
There were two people killed, two white
was something like that really necessary?

And I get to see some, what some Southerners think is that if the civil rights movement had taken place in the sense that it did with the sit-ins and all, that today, socially, there'd be a better situation between whites and blacks.
And one comment that was made is that a lot of the legislative
progress that was made during the 50s and the 60s is now being overturned in the 80s.
For instance, with what is that thing in Texas that came up about the tuition?
Being able to take your tuition to anywhere that you go, want to go to school.
That seems to me like a recall of that to what Virginia was trying to do.
Well, I think that all these things are ups and downs.
You move one inch ahead and you retreat one mile behind in human rights and civil rights.
And that's the way of humanity.
As long as we have humans, there's going to be that reaction phenomena.
So I can't answer it except to say yes, I think.
There are some things that are, in some parts of the country, maybe not as favorable as they ought to be or they should be.
But overall, comparing 1963 with 1985, I see many more favorable things now than then.
That's the only way I can answer it.
You know, with specific situations, you can always find things that are different.
I guess one thing about Martin Luther King, that was the second time that you heard him speak.
When was the first time?
Yeah, second time in person, but of course I heard him continually during that era on television, the radio, and so forth.
But the first time we had invited him to come to be our Wesley Foundation speaker, and of course he was with us for a number of days, and I got to know him in the context of
better than, you know, often you get to know most people, which, you know, you hear them at a rally, or a speech, and that's it.
What were your impressions?
I felt that he was a sincere person who was attempting to live out the convictions of his life.
His father was a pastor in Atlanta, and he
definitely, I thought, was trying to bring to our consciousness the fact that our Christianity was not doing what the New Testament had indicated that it should be doing in this time in history.
And I think that he was doing what a preacher ought to be doing who was convicted to bring both personal and

social justice to us and of course I saw in him the prophetic voices of Amos and Hosea and others in the Old Testament who tried to help the Jewish people long before Christ to be more compassionate to each other as well as their neighbors and bring justice and
understanding to the people that were living in those BC times.
What was the response of the community to his presence?
Well, the Mankato community in general were impressed with his oratory and his sincerity and the fact that he was trying to, as a person, unright the wrongs of humanity throughout history.
through his movement, Southern Leadership Travellers.
He was brought by Wilbur Gross, is that right?
Well, he was brought by a number of us who felt he was a local witness to some of the convictions that we believe are inherent in the Old and New Testament.
Did his wife come along with him?
No, he didn't.
Would you like to make any general conclusions or further comments about that period of time?

Well, I would say that I was glad that I lived through that era of time because it helped me understand how important it is as a person who has been given many good things, such as a religious heritage that sees a

uniformity and equality inherent in our faith and also I'm thankful for our political heritage and the fact that we have a constitution that says idealistically what we ought to be and I'm thankful also for having an educational opportunity in this country to have
had professors and fellow students who helped me understand the importance of all of these things.
I think that era of history is one that really, as I said, did more than the Revolutionary War or the Civil War to help humanity see
that we need to focus in on the values of human beings, that all human beings have worth in terms of their life.
And out of that came an appreciation, not just for blacks, but for browns and yellows
reds and all the other rainbows of humanity.
I think that also that period of history helped us see how utterly difficult it is always to change our legal system and our institutions
and even our families to appreciate people who are different than we are.
And I think that it's helped me individually to try to bridge the gaps and the barriers that are ever around us in trying to relate to people, listen to people, understand people.
I personally believe that

most important thing that we can do as a country and as members of the human race is to gain these kinds of understandings and to try to live them out so that we can avoid human prejudice and conflict, violence and war.
I think that this is something that goes beyond
Any ideology or religion, it should universally be in our veins to do that.
Unfortunately, it isn't that way genetically, so we have to work in a sociological way through the institutions of politics, religion, the family, in the socialization of
of people, and I think it differentiates us from the animals when we do that.
When we don't do it, I think we are back to stark jungle.
In fact, the jungle, and I've lived in the jungle, is actually better than the jungle we create with our prejudice.
The raw jungle is a safer environment, more safe environment, I find,
than the jungle that we have created by our prejudices.
Here is a quote I found.
I guess it was about that violence that I was trying to play here.
I was trying to talk about something that Martin Luther King said.
He said, I've almost reached the regrettable conclusion that the Negro's greatest stumbling block in the stride towards freedom
is not the white citizens' council or the Ku Klux Klan, but the white moderate who is more devoted to order than to justice.
That's what I was trying to say.
I guess that was one thing I was reading about this Ku Klux Klan.
Well, I think, you know, that it's, that's an interesting problem, because later on, when I started to work with blacks,
on various projects.
I was rejected because I was seen as a paternalistic white who was cultivating their interest in it.
Now, since the law gave them equality again, of course in the law, but we weren't enforcing it, that I was
interfering with their understanding.
They didn't need any white leadership anymore.
They could carry it themselves.

And all I've got to say for the poor black, or for the person that has that mentality, and I speak right to Martin Luther King here, there's no man, Martin Luther King or anybody else, that I wouldn't challenge.
I'm a thinking person too.
and I would challenge Martin Luther King to say that we can't really get along without each other.
I don't think he'd disagree with that.
But that we really haven't got time to blame different kinds of people either.
I think he said some of that, probably some of the bitterness that he experienced
And again, not being treated probably equally.
There were some liberal whites who got into the southern Christian leadership movement and assumed leadership and took it away from some of the blacks.
And I think that's what he was, he probably was striking back at that and he probably resented that to some degree.
I don't know.
He's dead.
It'd be interesting to
to talk with him if he were here about that.
But I think it's probably some of his own feelings and resentment that even in this movement, there were some whites who put order, peace, somewhat like the problem of...
Sometimes it's just like in all of life, you've got to go through a conflict
before you can get to the other side sometimes.

And sometimes we, yeah, we would rather not talk to each other, we'd rather not confront one another, we'd rather not say one another, to one another, the things we ought to say because we think we might hurt each other, and yet if we remain silent and we don't say it, ultimately in the long run we'll be guilty of problems.
And I think I've made those mistakes too, and I continue to make those mistakes.
And there are some people who are not close friends of mine because I do speak my mind to them.
And sometimes it was in case and in times of trying to help save their life, be it from drugs or whatever, that I said what I said.
And I'm sorry, I thought more of their life than I did of our friendship.

And that may be also true of some of the people who are my relatives and friends who I've spoken directly to, not in anger, but just, you don't have to say it in anger, it just still can be misunderstood, you know.
And I said it because of their health and their life more than it was interesting.
If I hurt them because I said it,
I said it.
I regret that I hurt them, but I don't regret that I said it.
Well, thank you very much, Dad.
Thank you for your good questions.
They were hard.
